==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tome
<hw>Tome</hw> <pr>(t⟦omac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>tome</ets> (cf. It., Sp., & Pg. <ets>tomo</ets>), L.
<ets>tomus</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ a piece cut off, a part of a book, a
volume, akin to <?/ to cup, and perhaps to L. <ets>tondere</ets> to
shear, E. <ets>tonsure</ets>. Cf. <er>Anatomy</er>, <er>Atom</er>,
<er>Entomology</er>, <er>Epitome</er>. ]</ety> <def>As many writings as
are bound in a volume, forming part of a larger work; a book; -- usually
applied to a ponderous volume.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Tomes</qex> of fable and of dream.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A more childish expedient than that to which he now resorted is
not to be found in all the <qex>tomes</qex> of the casuists.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tomelet</ent>⟦br⟧
